People Notes

What are People Notes: Private Noteworthy Knowledge about Me and Others

People are unique, each with distinct experiences, backgrounds, perspectives, and life events. In digitally enabled work relationships, it’s a constant struggle to maintain a cohesive view of individuals—our interactions are scattered across emails, chats, meetings, and times. People Notes builds a comprehensive knowledge hierarchy of the people you digitally interact with. It is grounded in the observation that humans don’t just store new information for later; we reflect on it and integrate it with our existing knowledge the moment we learn it. This is in contrast to “Copilot reasoning,” where most analysis happens only after a query. With People Notes, key insights—“notes”—about you (Me) and those you interact with (You) are captured as they arise, forming a digital memory of people that’s easily interpreted by humans and ready for Copilot consumption. Notes are private to you, extracted out of your communications with others.

 

Example: Imagine discussing fatherhood in a chat with a colleague. A mention of “working hours between 11 pm and 3 am” probably doesn’t mean they actually work late shifts—it’s likely about a newborn’s erratic sleep schedule. People Notes recognizes this and records something like: “X has a child named Y, who often sleeps from 11 pm to 3 am.” Similarly, a Me note might say, “I have a child named Niki, born in late December,” inferred from context about the child being two months old in February.

 

Visit "aka.ms/pintfeedbackportal" to see your own people notes. Smart Notes (representation of People Notes in LPC) is available for MSIT users (see screenshot to the right).

Here is how we envision People Notes:

  • People Notes are comprehensive and ongoing narrative about internal and external people created by reasoning over user interactions across different timeframes and mediums (1P and 3P).
  • People Notes represent a hierarchy of knowledge abstraction, including notes of notes and People Journal (the most abstract glanceable knowledge about people), going beyond single-level reasoning.
  • People Notes are enriched proactively from different sources, including other notes, notes about other people, and internal and external sources for discovery and learning purposes.
  • People Notes are shareable safely to promote the people level knowledge to team and corporate level.
  • People Notes is the first wave of X-Notes, a distilled and enriched knowledge across many entities, that can connect to agents (e.g., Copilot Agent).

Notes quality attributes

As we explore the expanding applications of People Notes, it is crucial to define what constitutes a "good" note in terms of its format and content. To ensure that notes adhere to regulations consistent with Responsible AI (RAI) and privacy standards, certain boundaries must be respected, detailed here. A note that honors these constraints is then evaluated as either a "good" (useful) or "bad" (not useful) based on two sets of quality attributes: 1) generic (intrinsic) quality attributes, and 2) scenario-specific quality attributes. These quality attributes refer to the “noteworthiness” of notes, information that are potentially important for me and I might need to remember them in the future. Some generic attributes include: 

 

  1. Private & People-Centric: Computed from data I have access to and visible only to me and involve at least one person (could be me or someone else)
  2. Concise, Specific, and Appropriately Abstracted: Brief, focusing on essential details, avoids vague statements, Captures the core insight without unnecessary detail, and balances open-ended context with scenario-driven focus
  3. Relevant & Durable: Reflects current reality and retains usefulness over time, worth remembering for future reference

 

See details here: people notes quality requirements and ARCH what are people notes

Why People Notes?

The People Notes effort created a foundation for personalization and a new breed of AI-first people experiences, introducing LLM enabled short-term and long-term memory capabilities in the Microsoft People Graph. This information is persistent, managed, condensable, searchable, and can be recalled by partners. Here are some user job examples leveraging people notes:

 

  • Leveraging You Notes: I use Bizchat to find out who is familiar with our HR Policy for expenses, and Bizchat uses People Notes to suggest a person who was mentioned before in my location or region. Bizchat uses People Notes to remember a context-specific expert rather than a generic company-wide result. This user job relates to knowledge based people discovery (KBPD).
  • Leveraging You Notes: I use Bizchat and want to know the name of the person I met from Northwind Traders at a conference last week, because I don't remember it. Bizchat checks my People Notes and gives me their name and relevant details. This user job relates to deep people refind (DPRF).
  • Leveraging You Notes: I'm a Bizchat user looking into a new partner team that I'm collaborating with on Personalisation. I start by asking who the team lead is and BizChat replies it’s “James Anderson” and then offers more questions it can answer via suggested chips. Clicking "When did I last meet James Anderson, and what did we talk about?". It uses information I already have about them and the topic to go deeper. It helps me remember things I might have missed to get me up to speed on our relationship.
  • Leveraging You Notes: As a user of BizChat I ask for the latest reach figures on our marketing initiative of free trial signs ups for my new product feature. BizChat responds with an apology, and generates personalised relevant suggestions based on information it does know from my People notes as a suggested chips. “Who can help me get this information? Answering: “Jenny Sanders in the Business Analytics team owns ensuring marketing campaign metrics for free trials sign ups for all features are captured and available.”
  • Leveraging Me Notes: I'm a copilot user looking for new trousers for a wedding, because my old ones are too tight. Copilot knows my height and leg size, and only needs my waist size. It shows me options and asks me for more details to improve the results i.e. waist size. People notes help by giving the measurements it knows, and copilot adds the extra waist size dimension to people notes. You could replace measurements with colours, styles, brands or other factors that users shop with. This user has a job related to consumer copilot personalisation. See this in action here: adaptive_user_representation.mp4 taken from HackBox - E+D Divisional FHL - March 2024 - Copilot Adaptive Personalization.

People Notes and AI Research

The knowledge encoded in a Large Language Model (LLM) is limited to its training data. In specific, local, contexts (such as M365 users), however, providing high-quality response to user queries require access to the user’s accessible local information such as their emails, documents, chats, and more. This knowledge needs to be “injected” into the LLM to enable the model to respond to queries that require this local knowledge. In-context learning (injecting “relevant context” into the LLM context) and fine-tuning have been the main solutions for this lack of local knowledge. While fine-tuning is possible, it might be prohibitively expensive due to the need for individual models, privacy concerns, and frequent model updates. In-context learning, however, is feasible, especially with the growth of the context size in more recent LLMs. The main challenge in this approach is the importance of “relevant context”: How do we find relevant context in an ocean of data? What does relevance mean from first place? It has been shown that Retrieval Augmented-Generation (RAG) based on semantic similarity metrics (e.g., cosine similarity in an embedding space established on some assumptions) on raw data is not effective, especially when it comes to complex queries, generic context (see examples here: Graph RAG), large contexts, and large datasets (Sam Schillace Sunday Letters, Pitfalls in Semantic Search, why_no_rag.docx). More recent approaches such as MedPrompt and Graph RAG are attempts to address the shortcomings observed in RAG. People Notes is among this group of methods, proprietary to M365 data (emails, chats in Teams, transcripts in Teams calls, Yammer posts, etc.) and technology (Substrate, compliant storage, etc.). All of these methods share the common goal of providing abstraction layers on top of raw data, enabling more offline complex reasoning and clustering of information so that the search for relevance is performed more smoothly with less need for complex online retrieval. In other words, they aim to ensure “RAG is more sufficient”.

 

People notes components

People notes are extracted from raw data and stored in a storage for consumption. While the architecture for supporting such extract and storage can be implemented in many different ways (ranging from a long text, a blob or a document, or as annotation in a graph), the general components that can be considered for People Notes can be still discussed. Here is a high-level view of the components:

 

 

There are 6Rs that establish People Notes pipeline:

  1. Recognize (select): Given a data point, this module decides if it contains noteworthy information.
  2. Refine (extract): This module extracts the noteworthy information, with some definition of noteworthy.
  3. Remember (store): This module secures storage of refined data for future access.
  4. Reconcile (consolidate): This module aggregates extracted notes and forms a cohesive knowledge base.
  5. Reason (maintain): Continuously analyses the notes to maintain or improve on the relevancy and accuracy of the stored information.
  6. Recall (expose): Tailored retrieval of information based on specific queries or contexts.

 

Frequently Asked Questions:

Where is the data coming from for People Notes? For a given user, the data is all the data that user has compliantly access to. Today, the data is coming from chats and emails. The next data sources in line are Transcripts, documents, and the rest of data sources.

 

How to test People Notes in Substrate Explorer? Here is the query: 

https://substrate.office.com/PeopleGraphVx/v1.0/people?$expand=emails,graphRelationships($filter=relationshipType eq 'PeopleNotes')&$filter=graphRelationships/any(t: t/relationshipType eq 'PeopleNotes')

 

How do I see my people notes? In addition to the Substrate Explorer, you can visit "aka.ms/pintfeedbackportal" to see your people notes.
